ata-gravity="n"><svg viewBox="0 0 875 1000" class="icon" height="1em" width="1em"><path d="m1 787l0-875 875 0 0 875-875 0z m687-500l-187 0 0-187-125 0 0 187-188 0 0 125 188 0 0 187 125 0 0-187 187 0 0-125z" transform="matrix(1 0 0 -1 0 850)"></path></svg></a><a rel="tooltip" class="modebar-btn" data-title="Zoom out" data-attr="zoom" data-val="out" data-toggle="false" data-gravity="n"><svg viewBox="0 0 875 1000" class="icon" height="1em" width="1em"><path d="m0 788l0-876 875 0 0 876-875 0z m688-500l-500 0 0 125 500 0 0-125z" transform="matrix(1 0 0 -1 0 850)"></path></svg></a><a rel="tooltip" class="modebar-btn" data-title="Autoscale" data-attr="zoom" data-val="auto" data-toggle="false" data-gravity="n"><svg viewBox="0 0 1000 1000" class="icon" height="1em" width="1em"><path d="m250 850l-187 0-63 0 0-62 0-188 63 0 0 188 187 0 0 62z m688 0l-188 0 0-62 188 0 0-188 62 0 0 188 0 62-62 0z m-875-938l0 188-63 0 0-188 0-62 63 0 187 0 0 62-187 0z m875 188l0-188-188 0 0-62 188 0 62 0 0 62 0 188-62 0z m-125 188l-1 0-93-94-156 156 156 156 92-93 2 0 0 250-250 0 0-2 93-92-156-156-156 156 94 92 0 2-250 0 0-250 0 0 93 93 157-156-157-156-93 94 0 0 0-250 250 0 0 0-94 93 156 157 156-157-93-93 0 0 250 0 0 250z" transform="matrix(1 0 0 -1 0 850)"></path></svg></a></div><div class="modebar-group"><a rel="tooltip" class="modebar-btn" data-title="Show closest data on hover" data-attr="hovermode" data-val="closest" data-toggle="false" data-gravity="ne"><svg viewBox="0 0 1500 1000" class="icon" height="1em" width="1em"><path d="m375 725l0 0-375-375 375-374 0-1 1125 0 0 750-1125 0z" transform="matrix(1 0 0 -1 0 850)"></path></svg></a><a rel="tooltip" class="modebar-btn active" data-title="Compare data on hover" data-attr="hovermode" data-val="x" data-toggle="false" data-gravity="ne"><svg viewBox="0 0 1125 1000" class="icon" height="1em" width="1em"><path d="m187 786l0 2-187-188 188-187 0 0 937 0 0 373-938 0z m0-499l0 1-187-188 188-188 0 0 937 0 0 376-938-1z" transform="matrix(1 0 0 -1 0 850)"></path></svg></a></div></div></div><svg class="main-svg" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" width="428.33333333333337" height="353.33333333333337"><g class="hoverlayer"></g></svg></div></div></div></foreignObject></g><g transform="translate(349,12)" x="349" y="12" title="codeHTML" width="524" height="562" class="codeHTML" name="codeHTML" rot="0"><foreignObject x="0" y="0" width="222" height="200" style="height: 562px; width: 873.333px;"><div name="htmlCode" style="zoom: 60%; height: 562px; width: 873.333px;" code="<div class=&quot;ch&quot;>
    
    <h1>Half-Wave Rectifier - DC Sweep Analysis</h1>

    <div class=&quot;ch-card&quot;>
        <h2>Circuit Components</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>V1:</strong> DC Voltage Source (swept from -20V to +20V)</li>
            <li><strong>D1:</strong> 1N4001 Diode (rectifier)</li>
            <li><strong>R1:</strong> 1 kΩ (load resistor)</li>
            <li><strong>Analysis Type:</strong> DC Sweep</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>DC Sweep Parameters</h2>
    <div class=&quot;ch-formula&quot;>
        Parameter: V1<br>
        Start: -20V<br>
        Step: 1V<br>
        Stop: +20V<br>
        Total Points: 41
    </div>

    <h2>Simulation Results</h2>
    <div class=&quot;ch-grid&quot;>

        <div class=&quot;ch-col blue&quot;>
            <h3>Input Voltage V(in) - Blue</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Linear relationship with V1</li>
                <li>V(in) = V1 (direct connection)</li>
                <li>Range: -20V to +20V</li>
                <li>Slope: 1 (unity gain)</li>
                <li>Represents the applied DC voltage</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class=&quot;ch-col red&quot;>
            <h3>Output Voltage V(out) - Red</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Negative Region (V1 < 0):</strong> V(out) = 0V (diode reverse-biased)</li>
                <li><strong>Positive Region (V1 > 0):</strong> V(out) ≈ V1 - 0.7V (diode forward-biased)</li>
                <li><strong>Threshold:</strong> Diode conducts at ~0.7V (silicon diode drop)</li>
                <li><strong>Slope:</strong> ~1 in forward region (after threshold)</li>
                <li>Shows rectification characteristic</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

    </div>

    <div class=&quot;ch-card green-border&quot;>
        <h2>Conclusion</h2>
        <p style=&quot;line-height: 1.6; margin: 0;&quot;>The DC sweep analysis reveals the <strong>transfer characteristic</strong> of the half-wave rectifier. When V1 is negative, the diode is reverse-biased and acts as an open circuit, resulting in zero output voltage. When V1 becomes positive and exceeds the diode's forward voltage drop (~0.7V for silicon), the diode conducts and V(out) follows V(in) with a small offset. This creates a piecewise linear characteristic: flat at 0V for negative inputs, and linear with slope ≈1 for positive inputs above the threshold. The graph clearly shows the rectification behavior in the DC domain.</p>
    </div>

    <div class=&quot;ch-card&quot; style=&quot;background-color: #e8f8f5; border-left: 4px solid #1abc9c;&quot;>
        <h2 style=&quot;color: #16a085;&quot;>Diode Operating Regions</h2>
        <ul style=&quot;line-height: 1.6; margin: 0;&quot;>
            <li><strong>Reverse Bias (V1 < 0):</strong> Diode OFF, no current flows, V(out) = 0V</li>
            <li><strong>Forward Bias Threshold (0 < V1 < 0.7V):</strong> Diode barely conducting</li>
            <li><strong>Forward Bias (V1 > 0.7V):</strong> Diode ON, V(out) ≈ V1 - 0.7V</li>
            <li><strong>Ideal Diode Model:</strong> Would show perfect rectification at 0V threshold</li>
            <li><strong>Practical Model:</strong> Includes 0.7V forward voltage drop</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

</div>"><div class="ch">
    
    <h1>Half-Wave Rectifier - DC Sweep Analysis</h1>

    <div class="ch-card">
        <h2>Circuit Components</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>V1:</strong> DC Voltage Source (swept from -20V to +20V)</li>
            <li><strong>D1:</strong> 1N4001 Diode (rectifier)</li>
            <li><strong>R1:</strong> 1 kΩ (load resistor)</li>
            <li><strong>Analysis Type:</strong> DC Sweep</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>DC Sweep Parameters</h2>
    <div class="ch-formula">
        Parameter: V1<br>
        Start: -20V<br>
        Step: 1V<br>
        Stop: +20V<br>
        Total Points: 41
    </div>

    <h2>Simulation Results</h2>
    <div class="ch-grid">

        <div class="ch-col blue">
            <h3>Input Voltage V(in) - Blue</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Linear relationship with V1</li>
                <li>V(in) = V1 (direct connection)</li>
                <li>Range: -20V to +20V</li>
                <li>Slope: 1 (unity gain)</li>
                <li>Represents the applied DC voltage</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="ch-col red">
            <h3>Output Voltage V(out) - Red</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Negative Region (V1 &lt; 0):</strong> V(out) = 0V (diode reverse-biased)</li>
                <li><strong>Positive Region (V1 &gt; 0):</strong> V(out) ≈ V1 - 0.7V (diode forward-biased)</li>
                <li><strong>Threshold:</strong> Diode conducts at ~0.7V (silicon diode drop)</li>
                <li><strong>Slope:</strong> ~1 in forward region (after threshold)</li>
                <li>Shows rectification characteristic</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

    </div>

    <div class="ch-card green-border">
        <h2>Conclusion</h2>
        <p style="line-height: 1.6; margin: 0;">The DC sweep analysis reveals the <strong>transfer characteristic</strong> of the half-wave rectifier. When V1 is negative, the diode is reverse-biased and acts as an open circuit, resulting in zero output voltage. When V1 becomes positive and exceeds the diode's forward voltage drop (~0.7V for silicon), the diode conducts and V(out) follows V(in) with a small offset. This creates a piecewise linear characteristic: flat at 0V for negative inputs, and linear with slope ≈1 for positive inputs above the threshold. The graph clearly shows the rectification behavior in the DC domain.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="ch-card" style="background-color: #e8f8f5; border-left: 4px solid #1abc9c;">
        <h2 style="color: #16a085;">Diode Operating Regions</h2>
        <ul style="line-height: 1.6; margin: 0;">
            <li><strong>Reverse Bias (V1 &lt; 0):</strong> Diode OFF, no current flows, V(out) = 0V</li>
            <li><strong>Forward Bias Threshold (0 &lt; V1 &lt; 0.7V):</strong> Diode barely conducting</li>
            <li><strong>Forward Bias (V1 &gt; 0.7V):</strong> Diode ON, V(out) ≈ V1 - 0.7V</li>
            <li><strong>Ideal Diode Model:</strong> Would show perfect rectification at 0V threshold</li>
            <li><strong>Practical Model:</strong> Includes 0.7V forward voltage drop</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

